# Explicit Scope, Safe Changes, Optimal Code

## Do only what was asked

- Implement **only** what the user explicitly requested. Do not add features, refactors, UI changes, docs, tests, migrations, or "nice-to-haves" unless asked.
- If the request is ambiguous, **ask** before expanding scope — do not guess and build extra work.
- Question-only or review-only requests → answer or review only; **no code changes**.
- Do not commit, push, or open PRs unless explicitly requested.

## Do not break existing code

- Read surrounding code and match existing patterns (naming, types, imports, abstractions, error handling).
- Prefer the **smallest correct diff** that solves the request. Touch only files required for the task.
- Reuse and extend existing functions/components; do not reimplement parallel logic.
- Before finishing, verify the change does not regress related behavior (call sites, props, API contracts, map layers, migrations order, etc.).
- Do not remove or repurpose existing UI controls, endpoints, or behavior unless the user explicitly asked.

## Write optimal, best-practice code

- Correctness first, then clarity, then performance. Avoid premature abstraction and over-engineering.
- No drive-by edits to unrelated files, dead code cleanup, or style churn outside the task.
- Comments only for non-obvious business logic — code should mostly explain itself.
- Add tests only when requested or when they materially protect non-trivial behavior introduced by the task.

## When blocked

- If a safe fix requires scope beyond what was asked (e.g. schema change, breaking API), **stop and explain** — do not silently broaden the change.
